Selector outperforms other methods.
From Tab.Â 1, we see that adding the Selector consistently outperforms MaxProb in coverage for all risk tolerances as well as AUC.
The strongest improvements occur at lower risk tolerances (e.g., 1% and 5%), becoming smaller as the tolerance increases (e.g., 10% and 20%).
Notably, CLIP-ViL with Selector can improve ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1% to 2.3Ã—\times that of CLIP-ViL with MaxProb.
Fig.Â 2 illustrates how, for low risk levels, the addition of the selector maintains noticeably better risk as coverage increases compared to MaxProb.
It generally appears that the more accurate a model is overall, the more it may potentially improve in coverage at low risk tolerances when using Selector.
For instance, when adding the Selector, we observe the largest improvements in ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1% and ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@5% with CLIP-ViL (8.83% and 3.84%, respectively), which also has the highest accuracy.
Meanwhile, Pythia has the lowest accuracy and exhibits the smallest improvements with the Selector at these tolerances (2.46% and 1.84%, respectively).
Fig.Â 2 depicts this between 0-5% risk, where the gap between MaxProb and Selector appears to widen as we move to more accurate models (left to right).
Lastly, we observe that Calibration can improve coverage beyond MaxProb as well, but less than the Selector, especially at low risk tolerances (e.g., 1%, 5%), and not as consistently.
Because Calibration modifies the output logits, it also slightly changes model accuracy.

Better accuracy â‡â‡\nRightarrow better coverage at low risk.
While accuracy appears to positively correlate with a better risk-coverage trade-off, the results in Tab.Â 1 also imply that higher accuracy does not guarantee better coverage at low risk.
For example, CLIP-ViL has 2.50% higher accuracy than ViLBERT, but, with default MaxProb, ViLBERT has 0.66% higher ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1% than CLIP-ViL.
AppendixÂ 0.C also shows that augmenting the VQA model training data with the selection function training data and using MaxProb still has worse coverage at low risk than when using this data for Selector training, despite having higher accuracy.
These results imply that improving upon the risk-coverage trade-off requires not only building more accurate models but also learning better abstention policies.

Still room for improvement.
Though the evidence presented in Tab.Â 1 and Fig.Â 2 show that coverage at different risk tolerances can be improved, these approaches still fall short of the best possible.
For example, in Tab.Â 1, the difference in ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1% between each model with Selector and their respective best possibles is still >>50%.
Although achieving the best possible may not be realistic, more work is needed to have reliable models with high accuracy and wide coverage that shrink this gap further.

Beyond its connection to VQA Accuracy (Lemma 1), Effective Reliability has several other advantages.
We show that it meaningfully correlates with risk-coverage (Tab.Â 2), yet provides a single metric to compare models.
This offers simpler comparisons that can be used to rank approaches (e.g., evaluating on a challenge server).
It also provides an alternative evaluation for settings where it may be easier or more intuitive to define a cost for an incorrect answer as opposed to a target level of risk.

In Tab.Â 1, Tab.Â 2, and Fig.Â 2, we report mean results over 10 random seeds for Pythia and CLIP-ViL (standard deviations in AppendixÂ 0.K), while we report single runs for ViLBERT and VisualBERT using existing pretrained and fine-tuned models.
All other results are single runs from the same randomly chosen seed.
Details of data and model setups are in AppendixÂ 0.I and AppendixÂ 0.J.

We evaluate Effective Reliability (Î¦csubscriptÎ¦ğ‘\Phi_{c}) defined in Sec.Â 3.1, which assigns a cost to incorrect predictions, a reward to correct predictions, and zero to questions on which a model abstained from answering.
This provides a single measure to jointly consider reliability (i.e., low risk) and effectiveness (i.e., high coverage).
In Tab.Â 2, we choose cost values cğ‘c of 1, 10, and 100, to observe how models compare when the consequences for providing an incorrect prediction become high.
Additionally, we can now directly compare to the original VQA formulation, where models do not have an option to abstain, denoted by a null selection function gğ‘”g. We also include Î¦csubscriptÎ¦ğ‘\Phi_{c} for the best possible gğ‘”g, where a model abstains exactly on those inputs which would result in incorrect predictions. As discussed in Sec.Â 3.1, this is equivalent to the model accuracy. Results are reported on the test set, with an abstention threshold selected to optimize Î¦csubscriptÎ¦ğ‘\Phi_{c} on the validation set. We include the corresponding risk and coverage for the selected threshold.

Cost implicitly controls risk and coverage. When the penalty for a wrong answer is high, one might expect a selective model to operate in the low-risk regime.
This is indeed reflected in Tab.Â 2, where the range of risk levels for selective models at Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100} (â„›â‰ˆâ„›absent\mathcal{R}\approx 0.6â€“1.3%) is much lower than the range of risk at Î¦1subscriptÎ¦1\Phi_{1} (â„›â‰ˆâ„›absent\mathcal{R}\approx 18â€“22%).
This directly translates to a similar trend in coverage, where selective models answer about 5â€“11% of questions at Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100}, and about 74â€“82% of questions at Î¦1subscriptÎ¦1\Phi_{1}. This shows that Effective Reliability behaves intuitively around the influence of a user-selected cost on model risk and coverage.

Tab.Â 3 provides ablations for the selection function design.
In the following, we distill the main observations.
Additional discussion is in AppendixÂ 0.B.

Selector requires multimodal input.
Tab.Â 3 shows the importance of using multimodal information for coverage at low risk levels.
When using each representation in isolation, we see that multimodal representations (rğ‘Ÿr, vğ‘£v, and fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x)) yield much stronger ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1%, ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@5%, Î¦10subscriptÎ¦10\Phi_{10}, and Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100} than unimodal representations (image v~~ğ‘£\tilde{v} or question qğ‘q).
For highly reliable models (ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1%, Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100}), unimodal selection functions fail (coverage â‰¤\leq0.02%, Î¦100<1%subscriptÎ¦100percent1\Phi_{100}<1\%), suggesting that building reliable and effective VQA models is a truly multimodal problem.
Combining all representations generally performs well, so we use this setup in all experiments.

Regressing to VQA accuracy is important.
We find that formulating the objective as a regression of the answer accuracy, rather than classifying whether the answer is correct, offers significant improvements (Tab.Â 3), especially at low risk.
This is likely because predicting the fine-grained accuracy allows the model to account for partially correct answers and learn to rank answers that are more correct higher, as opposed to classification where the distinction between partially correct answers is lost.

Selector Architecture.
AppendixÂ 0.B presents results using different Selector architectures, where a less complex architecture can degrade performance, but a more complex one does not necessarily improve it.
Together with Tab.Â 3, we find that, rather than the network layout, the input to the Selector and optimization target are more critical to the performance when using the Selector.

Extending the discussion in Sec.Â 5.4, we are isolating the effects of different features/modalities on the risk-coverage trade-off when using Selector.
In this direction, we experiment with different input representation variants from CLIP-ViLÂ [69] in Tab.Â 3 by ablating the question qğ‘q, multimodal rğ‘Ÿr, and answer fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x) representations as well as different image representations.
For image representations, we ablate the usage of the visual representation v~~ğ‘£\tilde{v} directly from the CLIP visual encoderÂ [63], as well as the visual representation vğ‘£v that is the concatenation of the respective pooled outputs from MCANâ€™s self-guided attention moduleÂ [84] and MoVieâ€™s modulated convolutional bottleneckÂ [58], which are visual representations that also contain multimodal information from the question.
Question representations are taken from the output of MCANâ€™s self-attention module.
The multimodal representation is the concatentation of the multimodal representations that are used as inputs to the softmax output (i.e., classification) layer of CLIP-ViL.
For the answer representation, we use the logits just before the softmax in the output layer.

The results in Tab.Â 3 show the importance of using multimodal information for coverage at low risk levels.
When comparing using each representation in isolation, we see that multimodal representations (rğ‘Ÿr, vğ‘£v, and fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x)) yield much stronger ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@1%, ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@5%, Î¦10subscriptÎ¦10\Phi_{10} and Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100} than unimodal representations (v~~ğ‘£\tilde{v} and qğ‘q).
We also observe that the answer representation achieves the best performance for ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@10% and ğ’â€‹@ğ’@\mathcal{C}@20% when each input representation is used in isolation.
Overall, we find that considering multimodal information (i.e., combinations of multimodal representations and unimodal representations from different modalities) to be most effective, with the top performers being the models that incorporate the answer representation alongside multimodal representations (fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x)+rğ‘Ÿr, fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x)+vğ‘£v, and fâ€²â€‹(x)superscriptğ‘“â€²ğ‘¥f^{\prime}(x)+qğ‘q+vğ‘£v+rğ‘Ÿr).

We find that while this noise does contribute to some differences in performance, it does not affect the rankings between selection functions.

Qualitatively, we observe that there tends to be a very significant overlap in unfairly penalized examples between selection functions, which is likely part of why the rankings remain the same.
Moreover, the amount of these label errors tends to be small, and the vast majority of questions contributing to the penalties in Î¦100subscriptÎ¦100\Phi_{100} across all models are properly marked as incorrect (âˆ¼similar-to\sim93%).

These results imply that the comparisons between different selection functions at high cost (or low risk) for a given model are still meaningful despite the potential presence of noise.
